17:42.737 --> 17:49.487
You may ask, and I can't answer it, because it came from Kenyon, and I don't remember what he paid for it.

17:50.480 --> 18:01.675
But I would say, it's certainly because it came off of Dickens' shelf, and he says so, that it's a very valuable book.

18:01.695 --> 18:07.984
Kenyon bought his books for the most part before they... Well, that's true.

18:08.004 --> 18:10.868
Dickens really hasn't been on the top for a long time.

18:11.135 --> 18:15.279
That must have been quite a moment for you when you actually put your book plate in the book.

18:15.419 --> 18:15.760
Oh, yes, it was.

18:15.820 --> 18:17.041
Next to his book plate.

18:17.061 --> 18:18.863
I wonder if you could tell me a little bit about that.

18:18.883 --> 18:20.265
That must have been a moment, actually.

18:20.285 --> 18:21.045
It was a moment.

18:21.586 --> 18:27.092
And not without some pluses and minuses.

18:27.132 --> 18:30.275
You know, maybe in a way I didn't want to do it.

18:30.355 --> 18:32.157
In a way I did want to do it.

18:32.177 --> 18:32.758
But anyway.

18:33.218 --> 18:34.419
But let's go on with me.

18:34.560 --> 18:36.121
Away from Dickens, we'll come back to him.

18:36.522 --> 18:39.825
You see, I have, again, Oliver Twist in parts, very rare.

18:40.177 --> 18:43.101
but I have two copies, and I also have presentation copies.

18:43.141 --> 18:44.203
Here's two presentations.

18:44.683 --> 18:51.212
Here's to MacReady and Oliver Twist, and here's to William Harris and Ainsworth.

18:51.252 --> 18:52.254
Have you had all these made?

18:53.075 --> 18:56.319
No, some of them I have made, and some of them just came that way.

18:57.160 --> 19:00.445
Moving on to another author, Poe.

19:00.465 --> 19:01.587
Are you enjoying this, by the way?

19:01.687 --> 19:03.149
Yeah, I do enjoy it, yeah.

19:03.169 --> 19:05.472
This is Mike Tamerlane.

19:06.213 --> 19:09.137
As you may know, for reasons that I don't know,

19:09.758 --> 19:15.284
Somebody cut a V in two places on this book.

19:16.084 --> 19:21.930
Some people guess that they did it to prevent anyone stealing it.

19:25.073 --> 19:29.398
But as you can see, there's a little V before and here.

19:32.461 --> 19:38.787
May I just... Well, the thing that probably makes it so rare...

19:39.188 --> 19:40.289
Tamerlane.

19:40.649 --> 19:41.430
Do you hear that tape?

19:43.092 --> 19:47.977
That's the black tulip of the American Antiquarian Society doesn't own one of these.

19:49.038 --> 19:50.399
It's a rare book.

19:51.060 --> 19:52.521
The reasons are probably many.

19:52.682 --> 19:58.047
One is that he didn't sell a copy of it that they know of, and two, it doesn't have his name on it.

19:58.067 --> 20:02.131
So if you found this in the attic, poems by a Bostonian, you'd probably toss it out.

20:02.331 --> 20:03.853
One, in fact, was found in Worcester.

20:04.113 --> 20:05.955
Yes, one was found.

20:06.475 --> 20:08.738
1827, he was a youngster.

20:08.838 --> 20:16.390
Now, there are some poems in the back of... Ballarat and Tamaline and whatever that... other poems.

20:16.770 --> 20:18.353
I have the manuscript on some of those.

20:18.373 --> 20:18.873
I'll show you.

20:18.893 --> 20:21.537
When you got this, did you take it home to California with you?

20:21.898 --> 20:22.318
No.

20:22.338 --> 20:23.660
I had to go through all the rigamarole.

20:23.680 --> 20:25.102
I had to go through all the rigamarole.

20:25.183 --> 20:29.409
I had to pay... shipping and insurance to ship it off.

20:29.549 --> 20:30.530
$700.

20:30.691 --> 20:32.874
Was it to ship it to insure it?

20:33.395 --> 20:35.638
Then, of course, I had to pay California's tax on it.

20:35.855 --> 20:36.275
Why?

20:37.376 --> 20:39.118
Because I'm a Californian.

20:39.138 --> 20:40.379
No, but you bought it in New York.

20:40.419 --> 20:41.821
It doesn't work anymore.

20:41.841 --> 20:43.222
You now have to pay the tax.

20:43.242 --> 20:43.923
They've got you now.

20:44.523 --> 20:45.484
They won't release it to you.

20:45.664 --> 20:48.627
Unless you pay New York tax, which is more than California.

20:48.887 --> 20:52.451
They won't release it to you until you show a form that you've paid the tax.

20:52.471 --> 20:53.572
Six and a half, yeah.

20:53.592 --> 20:57.676
So what started out at $150,000 ended up at $170,000.

20:58.456 --> 21:03.081
So you had to do the 10% freemium and then everything else.

21:03.161 --> 21:03.821
That's exciting.

21:03.901 --> 21:04.562
This book...

21:05.943 --> 21:11.830
Murders in the Rue Morgue is interesting because there's a mystery connected with it, which I'm trying to solve.

21:18.138 --> 21:33.958
This has a, on the wrapper, it's the prose romances, Murders in the Rue Morgue and the Man that We Used Up, and the Philadelphia Publisher in 1843 was George B. Zeber, Z-I-E-B-E-R, and company.

21:34.428 --> 21:37.772
No other copy has the Zebra publisher.

21:38.273 --> 21:47.765
Most of them that are known, they're only, you know, five or six or seven or eight or nine, whatever they are, have either no wrappers at all or they have what they call the Graham wrapper.

21:48.446 --> 21:55.835
This copy also has a couple of little editor's pencil marks in it, which Poe was known to do.

21:56.496 --> 21:57.858
I'm not saying he did this copy.

21:59.400 --> 22:03.625
What we do know is that George Zebra...

22:03.757 --> 22:10.183
Poe wrote a letter to a publisher saying, I'm sending you some of my works through my agent, George Zebra.

22:10.203 --> 22:13.826
So we know that Poe knew him, so that much is established.

22:13.846 --> 22:16.329
We also know that Zebra published a lot of books.

22:16.349 --> 22:19.251
There just isn't any proof that he published this one.

22:19.852 --> 22:20.753
What's your guess, Taylor?

22:20.953 --> 22:21.774
Randall.

22:21.794 --> 22:22.154
Randall.

22:22.494 --> 22:25.217
Well, David Randall, who I'm sure you probably know that name.

22:25.237 --> 22:31.823
David Randall, when told of this copy, wrote in his book,

22:32.596 --> 22:33.617
which I have somewhat.

22:33.637 --> 22:35.159
That dupt him large enough.

22:35.740 --> 22:38.623
That this was a phony, not a real copy.

22:39.724 --> 22:51.117
And when the George people decided to auction the book, they got a hold of David Randall and said, we don't want to auction the book until we know its authenticity.

22:51.658 --> 22:52.559
Would you examine it?

22:52.779 --> 22:53.660
And he did examine it.

22:53.700 --> 22:55.002
And then he wrote an apology.

22:55.583 --> 23:00.308
And he said, never again will I ever brand the book phony,

23:00.524 --> 23:01.566
that I haven't examined.

23:01.586 --> 23:03.889
He said, it's absolutely... Oh, he hasn't examined it?

23:03.949 --> 23:04.790
He had never seen it.

23:05.071 --> 23:06.333
That's not good.

23:06.353 --> 23:09.357
He came up to the real book business, too, before he went out.

23:09.417 --> 23:11.981
So we have his letter saying that it is authentic.

23:12.061 --> 23:13.764
He doesn't understand Graham's title page.

23:14.225 --> 23:15.547
No one does.

23:15.927 --> 23:16.768
Well, there are two theories.

23:17.069 --> 23:21.055
One is that Poe gave it to Graham, nobody ever bought it, and he switched to Zebra.

23:21.215 --> 23:26.503
Or he gave it to Zebra, nobody ever bought it, and then he switched to Graham.

23:26.523 --> 23:28.506
Or Graham or Zebra

23:28.958 --> 23:31.841
Just took it upon themselves to put a title page on.

23:31.861 --> 23:35.144
Is this stuff that you've researched yourself?

23:35.164 --> 23:36.446
Yes, I've done a lot of research on it.

23:36.846 --> 23:38.428
I haven't solved it.

23:38.448 --> 23:51.221
Here's my Raven and Rappers, the companion copy that went in the soil with the last big sale in New York, which sold somewhere near $50,000, I think.

23:52.142 --> 23:56.687
But this is the Raven and other poems in the Rappers.

23:59.030 --> 24:04.938
See, the whole suggestion that the paperback is an invention of after World War II, isn't it?

24:04.958 --> 24:09.965
It's a wonder they exist at all.

24:09.985 --> 24:13.129
In that state, which is extraordinary, 150 years old.

24:13.269 --> 24:14.611
There's nothing terribly unusual.

24:14.631 --> 24:18.677
This is just a tale of the grotesque in arabesque, which is a nice copy.

24:18.697 --> 24:20.499
This was from the Strader collection.

24:21.641 --> 24:22.462
Stralem.

